<Response>None</Response>< Text>
Busy on the weekends?  Heck yes!  A hip joint and franchise that knows it and their main focus group I'd say would the be twenty somethings.  I didn't have a bad experience here.  Nor would I say it was stellar.I came to Floyd's shortly after moving into the neighbor hood after I cruised by it on my single speed.  I looked it up on Yelp and decided to take a chance on it.I didn't have a particular style in mind, but I knew I wanted to get a trim done as I was trying to grow out my hair.  I let the stylist have free reign and came out looking clean and with all my limbs in tact.  Suffice to say I will be back...In other news, I believe it's all about finding a place you deem affordable and finding a stylist that you like and develop a business relationship with.

Pros
* Straight razor finish
* Massage
* Atmosphere
* Beautiful people
* Cost/Value
* Accepts appointments
Cons* Busy

Review date: 10/15/2008</Text>

<Time>1618170880885<//Time><Rating>5</Rating>< Text>
A piece of California history you should visit as a side trip through 395. Not necessarily a destination. Due to Covid restrictions the visitor center is closed. Make sure you are careful in the parking lot as big rocks scattered can do some damage to your tires. Also ensure you have quarters for the feeders. Washrooms available.<//Text>

< rating>
5<//rating>
< review>
Unfortunately it was closed due to COVID19 but still got to feed the trout and ducks in the pond. There's feed in the machines that only cost a quarter for some feed.

It's a nice relaxing spot to stop and take a break, admire the old fish hatchery, and relax for a moment next to a pond.< /review>

< Date>
1599060426262< /Date>
<Response>None</Response><Rate>5</Rate><review>At the small souvenir shop, the curator is friendly and will tell you about the Hatchery's history after your self-tour (donations accepted!). The place experienced a devastating mud-slide & flood a few years ago which ruined the breeding pools, so no more fish are produced here. But the giant pond outside is full of the giant rainbow trout that you can feed -  like a koi pond. Awesome side- diversion off highway 395 near Lone Pine, CA.<//review><user>117988994310463520918< /user><GmapID>0x80bfbee762a9330d:0xc4e51b5793d63277</GmapID></record></dataset><record>
<Gmap_id>0x80bfbee762a9330d:0xc4e51b5793d63277</Gmap_id>< user_name>
Mark Fischer</user_name>
< rate>
5< /rate>
<time>1543009553543<//time>< Text>
Super nice people, volunteers that are rebuilding and managing the hatchery. Please think about making a  donation. Also I recommend buying some fish food and going to the trout pond, it's well stocked and includes some huge rainbow trout, including one absolute tank of a rainbow, by far the largest one I've ever seen.< /Text>

< Text>
Amazing place to step into history and enjoy the wonderful surroundings of the Sierra Nevadas, chill in the park and feed some fish. Car show is a blast!</Text>
<Name>Hayden Campbell<//Name><time>1554266169437</time></record></dataset><record>
<username>Glenn Robins</username><Rating>5</Rating>< review>
I hiked from the truck stop to the hatchery and along the way discovered a nature trail, spoted 4 deer and crossed a rushing stream before entering the hatchery from above and behind. This gave me a unique experience for my first visit to the site. As I crossed through the abandoned and dry brood tanks to the rear of the hatchery I took many photos, all from varying perspectives. But it wasn't until I came around to the front and saw the pond that the magic really happened. The hatchery was closed due to a lack of a volunteer but I still enjoyed the visit and spoted many large trout in the pond (Polorized sunglasses made that possible) and of at least 2 species. I hiked down the entrance to the hwy to return. Overall about 3.5 miles and a very pleasant hike.< /review>

</record></dataset><record>
<Text>This was a nice place for us to stop and stretch our legs on the way home from Mammoth to LA.  Entrance and parking are free.

Inside the visitors center is a gift shop and hatchery.  We learned about the history of the native fish and how trout are raised and used to stock the lakes in the Eastern Sierras.  We even got to see some baby trout in the hatchery.

Outside, there are grassy areas, picnic tables and clean, flushing bathrooms.  There is a small pond filled with huge trout (but no fishing allowed).  There are fish pellets you can buy for 25 cents from a coin machine.  The fish gobble this stuff up and its fun to watch the fish fight over the food.</Text>< date>
1560834517719</date>

<name>Jonathan Kennedy< /name><date>1574719345124</date>< Rate>
5< /Rate>
<Text>This place brought back memories of when my dad took us here when I was little. It's no longer producing fish but they had one trough operating that had some fish in it, which was enough to make me remember the dozens of troughs in two rows that were full of tiny fish swimming frantically around. Every trough had a different size of fish in different stages of development. When they were big enough they would be taken to the lakes and rivers of the Sierra. I also remembered the sort of dank smell of so much water inside a building, similar to the smell of an indoor pool. My dad passed a few years ago but I will always appreciate the many interesting places he took us to.<//Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Resp>

Take a lunch and sit in the soft grass to eat.
The bathrooms are clean.
Staff is friendly.< /text>

< review>
I have to say, I was most impressed with the staff at this location. Our family was greeted by Steven as soon as we walked in the store, even as he was working with another customer. He was smiling and friendly, which is a stark contrast to our experience at our previous network provider. The other staff members were all busy restocking, cleaning and waiting on another customer in the store.

With the uptick in school shootings and lockdowns, we wanted our children to have phones for emergency purposes. We were not well schooled in options and Jesseca, the manager, sat with us and provided myriad options as well as plans. While we were working with Jesseca, Brianna, the assistant manager, showed our children the phones so they could try them and see what would work best for them. It took us a bit, but we zeroed in on the right phones and plan.

As we were working on the paperwork, Jesseca noticed my phone and asked if I had seen the new IPhone 10‚Äôs. I had not, so she showed us the phones and checked my plan. It turns out I was due for an upgrade and didn‚Äôt know it. Alex, another employee, went to the back to check the inventory to ensure they had the IPhone I wanted. Jesseca checked my plan to see if I had the correct one for my usage and I did not. She put us on a family plan, saved us money, got emergency phones for our children and even checked our DirectTv plan to see if it needed adjusted.

Time is something we don‚Äôt have enough of, so to have a salesperson, let alone an entire staff, care enough to check our phones & plans to get us the best deal, was truly a time saving and refreshing experience. Steven and Alex, along with Jesseca, also worked with us to ensure we all understood how to use our new phones. We have since sent in three of our friends for family plans.

I can see why they were all smiling when we arrived. It is obvious they enjoy working together and their job. Thank you all for a truly wonderful phone shopping experience!< /review>

< review>
Despite my complaint, I gotta admit that their food tastes great. I'd say it's one of the better Greek restaurants. But frankly, it's disgusting when my friends and I find a hair strand every two months.

First time it happened was in January and we let it go because we understood that everyone's prone to mistake. Second time it happened was in March and we notified the owner and manager; I noticed that some employees weren't wearing head wraps so I told them about it. They said they'll be careful. It happened for the third time today.

This has been going on every third or fourth order we placed for the past seven months, which is a clear sign that the owner and managers fail to acknowledge this problem and don't care about fixing it.

And this is for some doubters out there: No, we did not finish more than half of the dish and returned it for refund or coupon.

It's disgusting. If they can't even prevent the most basic issue like this, imagine countless other sanitation issues that are ongoing in the kitchen. This restaurant's cleanliness and sanitation is way below normal.

Don't go to this restaurant; it's disgusting and its owner and managers don't care if you swallow a strand of hair in your plate or gyro. If you still go here, enjoy looking out for a strand of hair before taking every bite.< /review>
<time>1565061487240< /time>< resp>

<date>1434822030969</date><Rate>2</Rate>< Text>
Ordered off the catering menu for a corporate lunch and we were HIGHLY DISAPPOINTED.  We ordered a large combo platter with lamb, chicken, gyros; an additional 8-10 gyros; a pan of veggies; and a few orders of falafel, dolmas, & spanikopita.  Paid approximately  $350.  The portions were very small...not enough to feed the amount of people we planned and ordered for.  The gyros were MEAT ONLY...? No pita bread, produce, or sauces.  The definition of gyro is meat wrapped in pita bread w/ produce & sauce.  When I called and told them, they explained their catering menu was meat only for gyros.  Seriously!? Where does it state that? Why would anyone assume that? Service was friendly and food was good but they lost our business.  The veggie pan was super expensive and was extremely small! Well, another Greek restaurant just got our business...@ least $400 per month.

of veggies veggies veggie</Text>

<user>110410324942643825684< /user><Resp>None< /Resp>< text>
I ordered a pizza online, which I have done many times with these guys and there is online tracker that tells you exactly the stages the pizza is in when they are making the pizza, which is great! I called on a very busy night and I expected it to be a long wait. It has been over an hour and it still hasn't shown that the pizza was even out of the "Prep" phase. I called this Dominos and right away, "It's on the way." So I was like, this is great! I guess the online tracker isn't accurate. 45 minutes go by and I am wondering why my pizza hasn't been delivered yet since it's only 1.5 miles away. Turns out, it has even been made yet. Once I called again, I finally see the pizza tracker move into the "Baking" phase. I wish they were just honest with me, I could have just cancelled and got something else. Instead I was just waiting there, and it took over two hours to get my ONE pizza. I called again and the person says, "If you want to cancel, I can cancel for you." I mean, at this point, it's been two hours, if I cancel now, then it would just have been two hours wasted. Nonetheless, quite disappointed that they just said whatever they could to keep my order. Could have just been honest, because I understood it was busy. I would have still come back to order again. Not anymore though. It was a good run guys.< /text>

< Review>
This is a great dinner spot for a cold SF evening. Our first impression was that the vibe was cozy, and while the place was packed on a Saturday evening, it wasn't too loud.

I would describe the menu as upscale comfort food. We had tomato soup and mac n' cheese, followed by the burger (not on the menu, but they said they always have it) and fried chicken with a side of brussels sprouts. Nothing adventurous, but everything was delicious. The fried chicken in particular was some of the best I've had. It was unbelievably crispy on the outside with some combination of spices and... maple syrup I think? And the chicken itself was still nice and moist.

I also loved the hot chiles in the  mac n' cheese and the chile sauce on the brussels, as I'm a fan of spice, while my girlfriend who doesn't like as much spice wasn't overwhelmed.

Portions are big. We had leftovers.

We will definitely be back.</Review>

< Text>
The beef wellington is all that at Maybecks.  Unfortunately,  I missed the ceremonial slicing bc we had trouble parking so we were late by 5 mins.  Arrive before 7pm if you want to see this.

The meat was incredibly tender and delicious. Perfection.

The "famous" garlic bread was okay.  It left a weird,  powdery after taste in my mouth and was very wet. I'll skip this next time.

BF says the steak tartare was the best he's ever had. And he can say that bc he's ordered it at some of SF'S finest and long establishments.

He also ordered the linguini with clams.  He rates it a B; says it was okay; pasta was a little gummy.

Cocktails are solid. A+

Desserts are solid.  A+ the ice cream flavors are outstanding. They offer a moan worthy chocolate molten cake that is heaven.

Service: the hostess was incredibly nice,  genuine and warm.

Our waiter was eric. He is very straight forward. He did his job. He wasn't warm, or engaging,  nor was he rude. Just straight forward. Probably best for introverts who prefer to eat alone at the bar.<//Text>

<user>118246307859485381903< /user>< name>
Michael ‚ÄúFishbits‚Äù Hraba<//name>
< date>
1466122477456</date>
<Rate>5</Rate>< Text>
Classic cocktail service without hipster pretension. They're going to know your favorite call, and they won't try to sell you on some overly-sophisticated "craft boutique bespoke cocktail" menu. They have it, but they respect people who know what they want.

I said my reviews would get shorter....

Go. It's loud, casual, and spendy... a deal breaker for some of the old timers in town. This is overly casual, and so I end up overdressed, as I am prone to do. The servers are fantastic and fun, while still being skilled and knowing boundaries.

Toasted Raviolis are wonderful. The Spagettini Uni is a must try. So interesting and balanced in the flavor profile.. no huge head explosion or surprise as so many restaurants attempt.

But just GO.. you don't need my ridiculous course after course description. This is a great treat and one of the lovely meals out that isn't overly dressy while still being modern fine dining without tablecloths... ie the heart and soul comes from the kitchen, and the front of house is there to execute that, and not the other way around.</Text>

<text>I had the pleasure of dining at Spaghetti Brothers last night and have already recommended the establishment to several friends, as well as my family. Will (GM) and Ron (the man behind the bar) took excellent care of me and the food that the kitchen produced is unparalleled in the area...I'd put the quality up there with the Mission's Foreign Cinema, no joke. First, let's start with the decor and general ambiance - its like stepping back in time a half-century to an older San Francisco. As for the food, the avocado toast with pecorino is the best I've had in SF and the halibut crudo was nothing short of exquisite. In fact, the fish was so good that I ordered the halibut entree, which was served exactly as halibut should be - flaky and tender, without falling apart on my fork. The cocktail list was designed by Will, who is himself an expert mixologist and a restauranteur I've been following since his work at Bix. I'd highly recommend one of their gin cocktails, like the Velvet Hammer. Last, but certainly not least, the dessert. I don't often order dessert, but had to try the Strawberry 'Good Humor' and it did not disappoint. Though reminiscent of the ice cream bars I used to get from the truck, this new take on an old classic redefined my appreciation for something as (seemingly) simple as strawberries with ice cream. I plan to come back as soon as my schedule (and stomach) allows. Bravo Spaghetti Bros!<//text>< pics>

<user>103561819551846819987</user><review>Excellent find for us one late Wednesday evening when we were all walking back from a concert at the Palace of Fine Arts. The staff are wonderful, friendly, and attentive (of course they've only been open for about a month). We the threesome  were very well taken care of throughout the meal.

Drinks we had:
The Dubliner - Perfect for the slightly cool evening, very nicely balanced though a bit low on the whiskey :).
French Negroni - Lovely gin in the Negroni. It even had BYRRH in the ingredients (sorry). My friend enjoyed this immensely.
Figone Negroni  - This was nice my friend said he liked it.

Food we had:
Spaghetti - Home made spaghetti was really just perfect. Ever so slightly under-cooked which to me is the perfect spaghetti and it was bursting with flavor if that's even possible. The restaurant lives up to its name.
Buratta - The cheese and the little gem lettuce was pretty good.
Clam Linguine - Linguine was again far above par the clams were perfectly cooked.
Prosciutto & Gridled Spiced Pears - The prosciutto had a lovely smell and texture and the pears really were perfectly gridled. Not at all overcooked (not easy).

Highly recommend the place for a nice evening dinner.</review></record>

<date>1454962269322<//date>< Rate>

<Text>I had heard great things about this place and I was super excited to try it. Ultimately, though, it fell short of the hype.

Came here on a Friday night around 8:00pm with a friend. The place was buzzing but not packed and we were seated immediately. We shared a few small plates:

Burrata salad - 5-stars. I was hesitant about the burrata salad as it was pricy and I feel like so often, a dish like this comes with a hint of burrata and a ton of salad. This was exactly the opposite. A good sized chunk of creamy, thick, flavorful burrata was served with the perfect amount of salt and pepper on top. It was complemented by crunchy hazelnuts and tart citrus, making a well rounded plate. I could have eaten this forever and I savored every last bite.

Sausage plate - 3-stars. The sausage was well cooked, but not as flavorful as I was hoping for. The dish overall felt quite boring... a single piece of sausage cut into slices, accompanied by a couple of greens. The salsa was the most exciting part of the dish, tasting strongly of onion and bringing some brightness to the plate.

Prosciutto - 4-stars. The star of this dish was the pear! I was so surprised. The prosciutto was good, but I mean, it's a standard cured meat, it's hard to make this really bad or really special. The pear though, that was everything. The pears were charred but not mushy at all, still incredibly firm. They had a strong black pepper flavor that came together nicely with the salty meatiness of the prosciutto and the sweetness from the pear. The textures matched perfectly. Really nice touch.

Overall, I wasn't wowed. I'd come back but I'm not running over.< /Text><Pictures>None< /Pictures><resp>None</resp><Gmap_id>0x808580d41dca9715:0x9686683c014d7b68<//Gmap_id></record>
</dataset><record>

<Text>I scheduled an appointment with Sears appliance repair because my 9-year-old Kenmore refrigerator was freezing food in the refrigerator. On the day of the appointment, the technician called me from his prior appointment to confirm, but I was on another call and could not pick up. He left a voicemail but by the time I heard it and responded to him 20 minutes later he had skipped my appointment and gone to the one after me.

In this day and age of robocallers, I don't know many people that answer the phone when the call is from a number not in their contact list. Sears should change this policy of its technicians calling on the day of the appointment to reconfirm the appointment after it has already been confirmed online multiple times.

Sears rescheduled my appointment for 2 days later and the technician came and diagnosed three issues with my refrigerator. Since one of the parts is not available any longer, I decided to purchase it used from eBay and make the repairs myself.

Sears does charge $129 as a diagnosis fee simply for showing up to the appointment, And this does not include the labor fee for doing the repairs themselves if you have Sears repair your appliance, then the $129 fee is deducted from the total cost of the repairs. if it's worth it to you to pay $129 to hear a professional diagnosis of your appliance's issues, then Sears may be a good option for you. <Text>Great place to be, greatest people to be around. Interesting and innovative crafts coming out of Covina CA. Has trivia, food trucks and games. I especially recommend trying their sours, some of which truly rank top in my all time list of must-have beers. I especially like that they don't use cheap shortcuts to get taste. They actually brew intelligently to get the flavors they want in their beer. Always love a place that brews without gimmicks. Can't wait to see what new things they roll out for the coming year. (Try their blueberry sour- if you can get it. I'd fist fight a nun in the parking lot for a drop.)

1-19-18
Update: a, new beer out of Alosta to recommend, one of the more interesting I've had out of the Azusa/Covina area lately, Amarillo Wild. Its a mild sour, sweet but tart, floral and refreshing, enough sugar that you can drink 2 or 3 but exemplary balance. If you like sours or beers that are light on the palate, absolutely a must-try.<//Text>< userid>

<Review>This place is so fun, but no relation to Game of Thrones! Located on the top floor of a shopping mall it's fairly easy to find. you have to park in the garage but as the plaza was empty it was easy.
There were just a few other groups dining here so not wait at all. We were seated and ordered drinks. Then you go to the bar where you build your own meal. They have everything from pasta to Chow Mein to the most amazing burger. I made a teriyaki noodle bowl which for my first time was alright but now I know better.
You build the uncooked meal in a bowl and then take it to the chef in the middle. It's like hibachi almost. He cooks it all right there in front of you. Or you can hit the salad bar. I could tell that wasn't touched as most of it was still stocked while the food bar was running low.
You also can ask the chef for a burger right there. This place is awesome. During lunch it's all you can eat for about $15. There's also a fully stocked bar and you can order desserts. If you're hungry, this is the place!< /Review>< Pics>

<Rate>4<//Rate><Review>Took our office staff there for lunch today.  After being seated you go through a salad bar line.  Then you go through another line with a wide variety of meats and vegetables.

You pack whatever you want into a bowl, then bring it to a large flatiron grill in the middle of the room.  It's kind of like a Mongolian BBQ.  You stand around the grill while the cooks work their magic.  Then it's back to the table to enjoy.

The food was surprisingly good, but the service was sliw.  We had to flag down our waitress a few times during the meal.  It was a fun experience.  I would go back again.<//Review><pics>None<//pics>< resp>

[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPeeeVXMz7SgjIVua49hT4cXenIaCx8vd6dulNt=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMy1QTlPUCIdON-AixCwBVQV4QhuxAKy452xGNk=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pictures>
<username>Simon Kaulius< /username>< Review>
Excellent cooked too order all you can eat. Choose all of your raw ingredients. Choose from a variety of Asian sauces, or Italian sauces, or Mexican sauces. Hand everything to the chef, and watch him cook your masterpiece.

Asian style... I recommend starting with a half container of either Szechuan or Sesame sauce, then experiment by filling up the rest of the container with some other sauces. If you really want to play it safe, just do equal parts Szechuan and Sesame sauce.

Italian style... I recommend equal parts Alfredo and Pesto. Add a garlic butter ball to your main bowl containing your noodles. Also add some raw garlic, and if you like it spicy, add some Sambal crushed red chillies to you're main bowl. Finally sprinkle some Sicilian seasoning over everything and hand it to the chef. Ask the chef to mix some of his own supply of shredded Parmesan to it while it cooks!

Mexican style... I recommend 2 parts Fajita sauce, and 1 part Cilantro Lime sauce. If you want to get crazy, add a garlic butter ball to your main dish containing your meats and veggies. Tell your waiter you'd like some tortillas and sour cream, and he'll bring them to your table.

Happy hour until 7pm! $4 beers!< /Review>

Great place with tons of options for every diet! Sign up for their email list to get some smoking deals! It's a clean, fun and tasty all you can eat Mongolian BBQ restaurant. Pick a base like veggies, pasta or rice then add toppings like carrots, tofu, corn, pineapple almost anything! Then choose a protein (or two... Or three!) In the evenings they have more seafood and serloin steak but lunch offers many options like crab, chicked, shreaded beef, cod etc. Then add some sauces (mix them together for more options!) And have them cook it together! You can also make custom orders like hot dogs, hamburgers and Philly cheese steak! The options are limitless! If your visiting the Disneyland area you need to check this place out!</text>

< text>
What a fun place! Plus great service. Our server Melissa was really attentive. We never had to ask for anything...we turned around and dishes removed, drinks refilled. The host (dont know his name) helped my friend whose daughter needed ice on her eyes (from a pool incident earlier in the day). He offered an ice pack (after seeing her put cucumbers on her eyes) without prompting. Plus the gentlemen at the bbq were entertaining, professional, and efficient. Everything moved quickly...food completely cooked, and fun to waThey seemed to have addressed the signage - it was clear we should put sauce on the side - signage at the ingredient bar and the server also told us. < review>
I've been here a couple times when visiting California, and i still absolutely love this place. I made some dang good seafood pasta. My only complaints are:
1. Suggested dish builds would be a great idea for people who don't know what to put together (my husband struggled with what to make)
2. At my favorite Mongolian bar in Utah, you put a stick with a number in your dish and they give you that number to put on your table and bring the food to you when it's cooked. I went as a nice date with my husband for our honeymoon, but we didn't actually get to sit and eat together the whole time. It was busy, but I can't imagine it's the busiest they get... And I had to wait forever for my food to cook and when I got back down he made his and by the time he got back I was ready to get more, and it kept going like that.
3. Trays would be amazing. They kept moving me around the cooking table and the sauces were spilling all over my hands cause I couldn't carry everything. I know it's more cleanup, but my hands could have been less messy if it had been an option. (if it normally is, I couldn't find them)<//review>

< review>
Ever encountered someone that plays hard to get? You do all this chasing, unsure if it's even worth your time & effort. I saw Fire and Rice multiple times on my social media feed looking all delicious without having a clue if I'd ever get a chance to try it.

To my surprise, Fire and Rice made an appearance at the Taylor Street Night Market in Downtown San Jose. I waited in line for quite some time, eager to try the Fried Spam Musubi. As soon as I was next in line to order, they ran out of Fried Spam Musubis-- I won't lie, that one hurt deep personally.

I went with the Spam & Egg musubi instead and it didn't disappoint! She was worth the chase although she must want me to keep chasing her for her Fried Spam Musubi (I suppose she's gotta leave some good things for me to wonder about for me so that I look forward to a second date)

My friend said the difference between the Fried Musubi and Spam & Egg musubi is that of course the Fried version is a lot crunchier, while the Spam & Egg version carries a lot more of the Spam flavor complimented by the egg.

Want to join the chase?
Go to their website & click on 'Schedule'. That's where they let everyone know where they're heading next.</review>

< username>
Jake Burgy</username>
<time>1407425922618</time>< Rating>
4< /Rating>
< Review>
This is your typical "Mongolian barbecue" restaurant - get your ingredients, bring them to the large grill and watch as your stir-fry is cooked.

What sets this place apart from other similar restaurants is that their ingredient selection is a bit more unique, and they can make a few different items on the grill that go beyond just stir-fry (they can do hamburgers and pizzas, and a few other things I think, as well).

I ordered what amounted to a Long Island from the bar, and it was very strong (and too bitter) - not tasty at all.

Overall, a good place. If you're a fan of restaurants of this nature (make-your-own stir-fry), I recommend this place.</Review>

<review>Wait times at Fire + Ice can get crazy, so come early. You can't go wrong with the Mongolian grill experience; I mean literally, if you don't like the food you selected who's fault is it?

Service here at the Anaheim location is superb, our hostess, Evette, was extremely attentive (and definitely on the Unicorn side of the Hot/Crazy Matrix). She brought out bread and tortillas and was very fast with my drink order.

The selection of food choices is endless and incredible, with crab, steak, and just about every meat you can imagine. I had shaved steak with Mango Habanero sauce (of a dozen to choose from). Also had a small salad and a cup of chicken noodle soup (perfect portion).

We didn't stay for dessert, since the bowling alley was next on our list and we traditionally have dessert there.

We will definitely be back. Remember, come early. We arrived at 4:30, no wait.< /review><UserId.>108806414935649540369< /UserId.><username>Steve Wiideman< /username><rating>5</rating><response>None< /response><time>1494116247881<//time><Pictures>None< /Pictures></record></dataset><record>

1452663688277</Time>
<Rating>4</Rating>< text>
Pretty cool place to watch your food cooked teppanyaki-ish and an all-you-can-eat too.  The service could have been a little better- the cooks looked a little tired and overworked, but overall enjoyed their cooking and style.

The food was okay quality, but when you consider the large variety of foods you can mix and create, the experience is pretty awesome.  The way the buffet works is you grab a bowl and place all the ingredients you want cooked (pastas, stir fry, fried rice, and burgers).  The pricing is also quite fair- $16 for Sunday Brunch Buffet (you also get some great pancakes and omelettes!)

Would come back.  Food and entertainment is a nice combo.<//text>

<rating>1<//rating>< text>
Walked in, service right off the bat was mediocre. Lady barely explained the procedure, however it was obvious, so we managed. She checked on us only once. Tables, menus, and walls were all dirty. Smudges and sticky. Just gross.  Assortments of meat and veggies was ok, sauces were too, but weird. Weird tasting. Just meh. Salad bar was pretty basic and that = boring. There was ONE soup and it was chicken noodle. Like who honestly cares about chicken noodle? Rolls were obviously old, previously frozen and could be used as shoes they were so tough.  Loud, unorganized atmosphere. Chefs were talking to friends or not at all, no showmanship. For 40 dollars it was just NOT worth it at all. Your money would be better spent at a nice place or a cheaper buffet! Really!<//text>

< Review>
I've been to Fire and Ice several times, on several occasions to celebrate various birthdays etc. We planned a dinner party at fire and ice for my sister's birthday and the food was great as always, but the service was appalling! I have never had such bad service and I've been to Fire and Ice many times. Our guests were embarrassed, the drinks were incorrect or salty, and our waitress NANCY was the worst. From the beginning of her introduction there was a horrible attitude towards the entire party. She approached our guests and did not give them time to look at the menu, but assumed they were not ordering and shared this info with guests at the other end of the table , by stating "are you going to order or are you going to sit down here like the other three on that end and not order?"....embarrassing (By the way, the other three ordered drinks and 1- ordered a meal)! Condescending, short in speaking with you etc. was how Nancy conducted herself! When asked twice to have someone come over to celebrate my sister's birthday, she forgot, and stated after being told twice,  that it is "our responsibility as customers to remind, and remind and remind her of this. " She then asked if it is still necessary since most of our guests are leaving......unbelievable! I was only aware of a small portion of this on last night at the party or I would have addressed this with the night me. We spent $500 plus 18% gratuity (we overpaid for service that was not delivered). She did NOT deserve the gratuity. Yet we paid....I called the restaurant today After finding these things out and still spoke with a mgr. With no real training on how to handle customer service issues....you don't cut someone off and say "I get it.. I get it, in mid conversation. She wasn't even listening to parts of the conversation, gave a half hearted apology claiming she apologized 10 times (who does that in REAL mgmt???)  And offered a free meal. Very disappointing. The goal here was to avoid this in the future, not request a FREE food item.
This company definitely could use training in customer service on ALL levels.  One of my favorite places failed and disappointed my sister and her guests on her 50th birthday.< /Review>

<Name>Rodney S< /Name>< Date>

<Rate>2<//Rate>< Review>
Why only one cook, Fire + Ice??

BIRTHDAY MONTH=BIRTHDAY COUPONS=HAPPY RODNEY

Free meal

One of the oldest tenants at Anaheim GardenWalk,  Fire + Ice is a Mongolian BBQ that has been on my to-try list for quite some time.  After stopping by KDOC in Santa Ana, Fire +Ice at the GardenWalk was a quick nearby lunch option.  And, having my free birthday month meal coupon in hand, it seemed like a plan.

The layout is simple enough.  Start by choosing your base (various noodles, rice, pasta etc.), then vegetables.  After that, comes the protein, sauces & prepared salads.  Pizza available at certain times, too!

Don't do what I did & mix the sauces with the meat.  Failing to heed the signs led the cook to inform me how mixing the two prior to cooking may led to the meat burning on the grill.

While there are a lot of options to eat, I found the choices of meat to be lacking in quality.  Initially excited to see blackened cod, the outcome after cooking proved to be rather dry & not very appetizing.  The shaved beef became a mush around the cod, and I found it hard to finish my plate.

Mussels & pork proved to be a step up in fare, leading to better enjoyment with my second plate.  I stuck to spring mix salad & Italian salad for my vegetables.

Service from my attendant was fine.  But, as I lamented to start the review, there's only one cook manning the grill!  I lucked out & just made the free 1 hour validated parking when leaving the GardenWalk.  Ample seating inside & al fresco.

Parking is at the Anaheim GardenWalk.  Validated parking is free for the first hour & reduced pricing for anything over.

A free meal is good, but the wait from having one cook, not to mention the lack thereof of quality meat options, are what soured my initial visit to Fire + Ice.  I'm glad I finally took the opportunity to check this place out, but unfortunately, I don't think I'll be using my free birthday month coupons going forward.  And, coming from a cheapskate like me, that's saying something!<//Review>

< Review>
Eh.....SKIP!! Quality of food is disappointing and the prices are too high for what its worth. +1 star for the good customer service.

Overall, the concept is interesting. They have AYCE Mongolian BBQ for $16.99 during dinner and $10.99 during lunch. There's a salad bar, a pasta bar, a topping/meat bar, and a sauce bar. You choose a pasta of your choice and top it with as many toppings that you can fit into a bowl and then you choose your sauce/seasonings on the side. Afterwards you wait in line next to the huge round grill located in the middle of the room and the chefs go to work cooking each person's dish.

Now the only problem with this concept is that the chefs at other Mongolian BBQ places usually mix the sauces for you but in this case there's at least 20 different types of sauces and seasonings and no instruction on the quantity or amount of sauce to use. Now if you are as clueless as I am with the variety of options then you are stuck eyeballing what to mix together and how much sauce to use and guess what? If your food ends up tasting terrible then its your own fault since you mixed it! I've tried two plates of food and the first noodle plate was terrible. The sauces I decided to use tasted funny and the udon noodles were the worse tasting noodles I've ever had. They were mushy, and stuck together in clumps. My second plate consists of only seafood since i didn't want to try my luck with the pastas anymore ( I picked clams, two different types of fish, and shrimp). Again, the seasoning didn't taste right and the clams were not fresh. Most of them were closed shut and those that were open tasted rotten. At this point I figured perhaps I was just having bad luck creating dishes that I thought would taste good so I had a taste of my date's concoction. Although his dish tasted way too bland and most of the meat and tofu were overcooked.

The only redeeming factor of this place is the good customer service. They consistently come by to refill water and check up on you to clear plates etc. I've always thought you can't go wrong with any type of Mongolian BBQ but sadly I was wrong. This place is pretty disappointing and I don't think I will ever be coming back especially since there's so many better options nearby (Cheesecake Factory, CPK, McCormick & Schmick's, Roy's).</Review>
<user_id>114461558056437807671< /user_id><user_name>Shanon Yu<//user_name><Resp>None< /Resp>< pictures>
None< /pictures>
<Rate>2</Rate>< Date>
1416421296866</Date>
<Gmap_id>0x80dcd7c31e793301:0x50dd0e8b33f0efbf</Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
< GmapID>
0x80dcd7c31e793301:0x50dd0e8b33f0efbf<//GmapID>
< Rate>
3< /Rate>
< review>
Should I eat Fire + Ice? It depends what you are looking for in your meal. On paper this place sounds like a great concept. If you are hungry there are plenty of options.

The things I wish I knew:
1. You can make pizza, waffles, omelets, hot dogs, Philly Cheese steak, and hamburgers! There is a sign on the wall for pizza, but if you walk past it you will never know. I didn't know the grill area has bread. Only regulars know this, but I was too full to try any of these.

2. Less is more! Remember you can always come back. Don't overload your plate go for a dish with simple and less ingredients. I don't recommend mixing too many sauces. Stick to the basics. Focus on one meat or one sauce helps.

3. Don't forget your veggies! I didn't have this problem but I watched a lady fill a bowl with every possible meat. If you do this, you are going to have a BAD TIME. I hope she has fiber.

PROS:
1. Services is excellent! The chefs are very friendly and attentive. Thanks for the pointers, because I was a newbie and didn't know where the line started at the grilling area. The food area is always clean full stocked.

2. Options! The options are truly endless. If this were an ice cream joint, Pinkberry and Baskin Robins would have nothing on this place.

3. Birthdays and large groups! No problemo! Getting a table was great and having restaurant patrons singing Happy Birthday off key priceless. Too bad the staff didn't join in.

4. Great for kids and people of all ages. This place is casual enough, but still has the great lounge/party music and bar decor for a late night hangout.

5. The food is pretty good. I was starving and this place hit the spot.

CONS:
1. Raw food. I didn't have too much confidence looking at the raw meats. The meat is stored in the same fashion as the salad bar, in cylinder containers with some kinda of cooling underneath.. maybe ice? Have you ever gone to the groceries store meat section and you feel cold suddenly? No this area is not that cold so what gives? Most KBBQ and Mongolian BBQ place shave frozen meat or if the meat is not frozen at least the meat is in a refrigerated unit. I'm a bit concern about the safety of this meat.

2. Over-cooked. My greatest fear is handing a chef a piece of raw meat and getting charred beef jerky back. The cooking process happens in a semi-circle so on a busy day the cook will just go down the flipping the food as he walks around the grill. Bad idea! Seafood and pork takes way longer than beef. I always try to be last in line for the best results. The first person has to wait until the chef cycle by a few times then he takes your burnt fried rice off the grill.

3. You get what you put in. I find random experimentation results in rolling the dice on flavor. If you don't cook, how will you know what goes in the dish you are trying to make? It would be nice some pictures to look or a menu on the table that tells you what goes in a chicken Alfredo and what doesn't go on a pizza. It would be nice to have a master chef to answer questions and make dishes for you :).

Things that need improvement (or make this place much better):
1. Separate the salad. I messed up my first round at First and Ice. My fault for starting on the wrong end of the line.  I was about to make a salad and I was collecting the items then I almost put raw meat on my salad. Please have a raw food area only.

2. Pre-cooked food! Maybe I'm just used to buffets, but if you are a gonna wait for 5 minutes plus for cooking at least give me something to munch on besides salad. I would like to get some fried or white rice to go white my stir fry but I don't want to wait in line again just to cook some rice.

*Sidenote* The next day I was playing R Kelly Ignition with my bowels. "Give me some Toot and some beep". More like the Dave Chappelle remix.<//review>

<userid>106110276524130659628< /userid><gmap_id>0x80dcd7c31e793301:0x50dd0e8b33f0efbf< /gmap_id><Pics>None</Pics><Rate>5</Rate><Resp>None</Resp>< Name>
Bob Stearns<//Name>
< Text>
Must go Good food Great place to bring your friends</Text>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<Resp>None< /Resp><Rating>5</Rating><date>1338739209384</date>< review>
I love this place, it has become at least a once a week experience, once it was up to 4 times in a single week.

It makes me a little sad reading some of the negative reviews from people that just don't get it. So for anyone that has not been and is reading this looking for guidance I am posting some help.

It is a LITTLE pricey, dinner is about $17. Not really that pricey, but it depends on what you get. There are unlimited possibilities, but if the first thing you do is grab a 1/2 burger and that fills you up then you are an idiot to pay $17, go to Carls Jr and get the same thing for $4 and stop your whining.

So for the $17 you get unlimited steak, chicken, pork chop, swordfish, shrimp, sausage, ground beef (which you don't need to take an 8oz serving), calamari, mussels, bacon, and several more selections. Add to the protein a huge selection of vegetables, pastas, buns, rice, beans, potatoes, tortillas and cheeses. All this and all you can eat for $17 there is not a better deal on the planet.

So you have unlimited selection and with a little creativity anything imaginable. If you are lost as to what goes together or what sauce to add to your concoction, just ask the Grill Chefs, they have seen it all. I have seen them make things that defy imagination. Like Lasagna, it was really good.

So then I hear complaint about groups. Let me start with Whaaaaa!!! Ok, stop whining. First, I have been with a group of 20, seen bigger than that. Now with any group you can not really engage in conversation with the person 6 down the table from you, so who cares if they are up or not. Second, when we go, usually groups of 4 or 6, we all tend to go up at about the same time, so then it is social as you see what all your friends are getting, then you can stand around the grill and socialize within your group or even meet new people, but you don't have to stand there. Let's say that you are the only one going up for more food at that time, you make your selection, put your bowls on the counter, then go back and join your table being gone for 2 minutes, knowing it will take 10-15 minutes to cook before you go back up to pick up your food. And if it is not super busy the grill chef or waitress will usually bring your food to you.

Personally, our group enjoys standing around the grill talking with the grill chefs, Kevin & RJ rock. I can not think of another restaurant anywhere that you can chat with the person preparing your food.

Service can be varied, there are some great waitresses, Lindsey, and even some that don't seem like they want to be there. But you know what... You are in control... as the customer you are paying them to be there, so if you get lousy service that can be reflected in the amount of tip you leave, if any. I hate being harsh, but if I never see my waitress then why would I pay her for clearing the table when I am done?

Lastly, regarding tipping, be sure to tip the Grill Chefs, they are the ones doing all of the work for you. They make your food whatever it is and however you want it prepared. They also are not tipped out of the waitresses tip, so if you feel they did a good job put the tip in the pitcher on the counter not just leave it on the table.</review>
